Introduction

A sommelier is an individual who is thoroughly trained with the knowledge of wine, arguably a staple in Western fine dining. They also get paid a median of $63,000 dollars for their work!. Lacking the cost to hire one for our purposes, could we instead assess the quality of wines based on their chemical properties? It would save costs and time, and its possibly quite easy to streamline the process of measuring these mentioned properties for future wines.

We have sampled 5197 different wines and have 12 different features to use in our modelling. We should highlight from Table3 that we do not have the full possible range of quality values. 9 is the highest quality value, and there are no wines ranked 2 or lower. If we were to treat quality as a category, we should be wary that we have an imbalance in category counts.

From Figure1, a few things are worth pointing out. Total sulfur dioxide and Alcohol are possibly bimodal, due to having two peaks in its distribution. Volatile acidity and Residual sugar have a lot of data points toward the right, which could indicate skewness. We should be cautious if we choose to use a predictive model that assumes our data is normally distributed.

From Figure2, we try to see if there are any features that have strong relationships with Quality. This is largely not the case. Additionally, there isnt a strong association between white and red wines for many of these features, besides perhaps Chlorides. There isnt even a strong association between Color and Quality. So at least in terms of direct relationships, itll be hard to find any. Maybe there will be more in the higher dimensions, but plotting that is outside of our scope (also t-SNE calculations take forever).

Models

# process data for ML
X_train = wine_train.drop("quality", axis=1)
y_train = wine_train["quality"]

numeric_cols = X_train.select_dtypes("number").columns
categorical_cols = X_train.select_dtypes("object").columns

numeric_transformer = Pipeline(
    [
        ("imputer", SimpleImputer()),
        ("scaler", StandardScaler()),
        ("poly", PolynomialFeatures(include_bias=False))
    ]
)

categorical_transformer = Pipeline(
    [
        ("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy="most_frequent")),
        ("onehot", OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore"))
    ]
)

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    [
        ("numeric_tf", numeric_transformer, numeric_cols),
        ("categorical_tf", categorical_transformer, categorical_cols)
    ]
)
pipeline = Pipeline([
    ("preprocessor", preprocessor),
    ("model", KNeighborsClassifier())
])

param_grid = {
    "preprocessor__numeric_tf__poly__degree": [1, 2],
    "preprocessor__numeric_tf__poly__interaction_only": [True, False],
    "model__n_neighbors":np.arange(5, 20, 1),
}

grid_search = GridSearchCV(pipeline, param_grid, cv=4, scoring="neg_mean_absolute_error")
# train models
_ = grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

We tried many regressors and classifiers, chiefly logistic regression with various solvers, linear, LASSO, and Ridge regression, and decision trees. These all gave a mean absolute error between 0.51 to 0.58. Ultimately we found the KNeighborsClassifer to perform best, as we will see.

For KNeighborsClassifer, we try \(k\) values 5 to 20, and also try out having polynomial features and interaction terms.

Results

# report model metrics
grid_search.best_score_, grid_search.best_params_
(-0.5077946053177,
 {'model__n_neighbors': 18,
  'preprocessor__numeric_tf__poly__degree': 1,
  'preprocessor__numeric_tf__poly__interaction_only': True})

Our best K-nearest neighbors classifier uses \(k = 18\) neighbors, uses no squared features, but does use interaction terms. It obtains a mean absolute error of 0.5078, which is as low as weve found.

Discussion

Being off by about 0.5 is not bad! Especially given that quality technically increases in steps of 1. We should note that, since there are no wines with quality levels 0, 1, 2, or 10, our predictor will never classify wines of that quality either.

Can, or should, a predictive model fully substitute a sommelier? Probably not! Tastes change, and wine variety is likely complex enough that itd be a poor idea to suggest the one same best wine to every consumer. A human sommelier is likely to be more capable of making tailored suggestions based on a customers preferences.

It should also be noted again that our dataset only contains measurements for Vinho Verde wine, so this model may not hold so accurate for other types out there.

Conclusion

A K-nearest neighbors classifier than uses \(k=18\) neighbors can make a fairly good predictor for the quality of a Vinho Verde wine. If the goal is just to assess the quality of new Vinho Verde wines, then this model will work great! We caution against using it with other types of wines, as this model is not trained on anything other than Vinho Verde. We also caution against using it to suggest wines to customers, as that is a more nuanced subject that may be better in the hands of a sommelier or a more complex machine learning model.
